Q. What is Lazy Loading?
A. Lazy loading = loading components/code only when needed (on demand), instead of loading everything upfront.
   Why we use it:
   üîπReduces initial bundle size ‚Üí faster first page load.
   üîπSaves memory & bandwidth (don‚Äôt download unused code).
   üîπImproves performance in large apps with many routes/components.

   If not used:
   üîπReact bundles everything into one big file.
   üîπLonger load time, higher chance of users leaving before app opens.
   üîπWasted resources ‚Üí user downloads code for pages they may never visit.

   Real-world example (E-commerce):
   üîπLogin page should load instantly.
   üîπWithout lazy loading ‚Üí Home, Cart, Favorites, Orders, etc. also load at the same time ‚Üí slow.
   üîπWith lazy loading ‚Üí only Login loads first. Other pages (Cart/Favorites/Orders) load only when user visits them.

   üëâLazy loading in React means splitting code into chunks and loading components only when required, improving speed and efficiency ‚Äî especially in big apps like e-commerce.



Q. Tell me d/f b/w calling a child component in this ways?
A. {/* <InnerComp /> */} - React treats it as a component (with props, hooks, lifecycle).
   Output - It works perfectly standard way of coding.
   This tells React:
   ‚ÄúThis is a component, manage it in the tree.‚Äù
   React will track its props, state, hooks, lifecycle, and re-renders properly.

   {/* InnerComp(); */} - Just a normal JS function call returning JSX, not a real React component.
   Output - It prints only InnerComp(); only 
   React doesn‚Äôt know you meant ‚Äúcomponent‚Äù ‚Äî it just sees a function returning JSX.

   {InnerComp()} - Same as above, but used inline in JSX to inject the return value.
   Output - It Prints the return value as State. But we can not use hooks, props, lifecycle method.
   Since it skipped React‚Äôs createElement step, React doesn‚Äôt treat it as a real component.
